It has to do with how you parse the result of your API call:

     for (let i = 0; i&lt;response.data.results.length; i++) {

            this.setState({movies: [{
                id: response.data.results[i].id, 
                title: response.data.results[i].title
            }]})
        }

Here you loop your result and overwrite the `movies` in state with the info of items result.. This will result in you only seeing the last result.

How about:

    }).then((response) =&gt; {
            this.setState({movies: response.data.results.map(item =&gt; ({
                id: item.id, 
                title: item.title
            })})
    });

You overwrite the movies object in your state for each result you get, thus only the last movie is added to the state. Read this article for more information on [managing arrays in state][1].

Here is a way to do it correctly:

    const movies = response.data.results.map(result =&gt; ({
      id: response.data.results[i].id,
      title: response.data.results[i].title
    }));
    this.setState({ movies });

  [1]: https://www.robinwieruch.de/react-state-array-add-update-remove

