answers.body_markdown:
Frankly, the question is too broad, because the answer really depends on what frameworks you are already using.
The thing is -  there are many popular frameworks today that provide implementation of retry logic out of the box.

For example:

* if you&#39;re calling &quot;critical API&quot; via feign, then there is a [built-in support for retry](https://github.com/OpenFeign/feign#retry).

* if you&#39;re using Spring&#39;s `RestTemplate`, then you might also use [Spring Retry](https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-retry)

* if you just need simple retry utilities, there are number of libraries like [failsafe](http://jodah.net/failsafe/) and [guava-retrying](https://github.com/rholder/guava-retrying)

However, if after considering alternatives you decided implement retrying manually with `CompletableFuture`, you definitely can do this. 

For example, here are simple utilities to retry:

 * Unlimited number of times:
```
public static &lt;T&gt; CompletableFuture&lt;T&gt; retry(Throwable throwable, Function&lt;Throwable, T&gt; operation) {
    return CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -&gt; operation.apply(throwable))
            .thenApply(CompletableFuture::completedFuture)
            .exceptionally(error -&gt; retry(error, operation))
            .thenCompose(Function.identity());
}
```
  Note: Here I assume, you can make some decision based on the instance of `Throwable`. Therefore, `operation` takes error as input and produces some useful result as an output. In your case, error - might be `critical API` call error, or `notification error`, useful result - successful `critical API` result.

* Fixed number of times (`MAX_RETRIES` in this case):
```
public static &lt;T&gt; CompletableFuture&lt;T&gt; retry(Throwable throwable, Function&lt;Throwable, T&gt; operation, int retry) {
    if (retry == MAX_RETRIES) return failedFuture(throwable);

    return CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -&gt; operation.apply(throwable))
            .thenApply(CompletableFuture::completedFuture)
            .exceptionally(error -&gt; retry(error, operation, retry + 1))
            .thenCompose(Function.identity());
}

public static &lt;T&gt; CompletableFuture&lt;T&gt; failedFuture(Throwable throwable) {
    final CompletableFuture&lt;T&gt; failedFuture = new CompletableFuture&lt;&gt;();
    failedFuture.completeExceptionally(throwable);
    return failedFuture;
}
```

